%T A394477 7,9,8,15,3,8,8,14,5,14,5,10,12,10,4,17,9,10,10,13,8,14,9,14,6,14,8,
%U A394477 23,9,9,16,17,6,14,9,17,11,18,11,27,9,16,15,17,11,24,10,25,11,19,11,31
%N A394477 Number of integers k in 1..n such that the numerator of the reduced fraction (n*(n-1) + k)/n is prime.
%C A394477 For each n, consider the set of n fractions given by (n-1) + k/n for k = 1..n. Equivalently, these are the fractions in the interval (n-1, n] whose denominators divide n. This sequence counts how many of these n fractions yield a prime numerator when reduced to lowest terms.
%H A394477 J. Huckstead, <a href="https://zenodo.org/records/21187177">Divisor-Band Bijections and Totient Shells in the Triangular-Fractional Grid</a>, Zenodo, 2026.
%e A394477 n=1: the only entry is 1; its numerator 1 is not prime, so a(1) = 0.
%e A394477 n=2: entries are 3/2 and 2; numerators 3 and 2 are both prime, so a(2) = 2.
%e A394477 n=6: entries are 31/6, 16/3, 11/2, 17/3, 35/6, 6, with reduced numerators 31, 16, 11, 17, 35, 6; the prime ones are 31, 11, 17, so a(6) = 3.
%o A394477 (Python)
%o A394477 from math import gcd
%o A394477 from sympy import isprime
%o A394477 def a(n):
%o A394477     return sum(1 for k in range(1, n+1) if isprime((n*(n-1) + k) // gcd(k, n)))
%o A394477 print([a(n) for n in range(1, 85)])
%o A394477 (PARI) a(n) = sum(k=1, n, isprime(numerator(n - 1 + k/n))); \\ _Michel Marcus_, Jul 05 2026
%Y A394477 Cf. A005563 (for k=n-1, the numerator before reduction is n^2-1, which is composite for n>=3).
%K A394477 nonn,easy,new
%O A394477 1,2
%A A394477 _Jeffery L. Huckstead_, Jul 04 2026
